title: Métro Abbesses
description: C'est la station de métro la plus profonde de Paris : 36 mètres sous le niveau du sol1. Deux escaliers en colimaçon et deux ascenseurs relient la salle des billets (niveau supérieur) aux quais (niveau inférieur). Le nom de la station vient de la place des Abbesses, qui fait référence à l'abbaye des Dames de Montmartre.

title: Hotel Relais du Louvre
description:
Nestled in a charming 18th century building, the Relais du Louvre is a welcoming 3-star hotel in the heart of Paris, in the 1st arrondissement. Located in a quiet and historical quarter, the hotel offers a customized reception and provides customers with advice and recommendations during their stay.
With a view on the Saint-Germain l'Auxerrois Church and the Louvre, the harmonious rooms combine the charm of old furniture with modern comfort. With  two well-fitted suites and an apartment, the hotel is also perfect for families.
Two steps away from the Relais du Louvre, we can wander on the Pont des Art and hang one of the famous love padlocks,discover the romantic Île-Saint-Louis or have a look at the strange Burren columns near the Palais Royal. For a little shopping, the Halles, The Marais and their numerous boutiques are just a few metro stops away.
http://relais-du-louvre-paris.com/fr/?lang=en

title: La petite pyramide du Louvre

tags.title: architecture - Do not use this category

description:
The small glass pyramid, like its larger counterpart, acts simply as an architecturally interesting skylight for the new underground vestibule added to the great museum. One may suppose objectively that, to the degree that esoteric mysterious qualities may be associated with the Pyramids at the Giza Plateau at Cairo or with this geometry in general, such qualities may exist here. 

With regard to the aesthetic appeal of the glass pyramids one may perhaps refer to the opinion of ancient Greece: 'Disparate elements make for the fairest harmony.' 

In general, we may attach meaning to our symbols, functional or not, as we wish. In that context, the original pyramids seem to have been intended as vehicles meant to assist the human soul in its quest for divinity and eternity, thus lending some more sublime and splendid meaning to our relatively short lives on our obscure little planet embedded in our obscure little galaxy. Truly, 'Tis the mind that maketh the body rich.' Let the mind feast upon the fields of the universe! Bon appetite mes amis! James M. Dec 2006


Louvre forced to rethink its glass pyramid - 27 Dec 2006 -
